</section>
<section xml:id="sec:graph-without-form">
<title>Graphing Without Formulas</title>

<!-- \label{sec:graph-without-form} -->

function is just a rule for associating a given input with its unique
output. For example, we could specify a particular function by writing
"take two copies of the input, multiply them together and return the
result as output."  This is a complete and valid description but it is
cumbersome to use.  This is why we've instead invented notation that
allows us to write the description succinctly as the formula
<m>f(x)=x^2</m>. It is easy to sketch an accurate graph of a function that
is given as a formula, especially using modern technology, because the
formula tells you the steps for finding the output for any given
input.

As mentioned earlier, formulas are the Holy Grail of modern science
and business.  But, despite what you have seen in your mathematics
education so far, very often we don't have such a formula. This is the
usual situation. If you own a trout fishery business for example, you
would love to have a formula that tells you how many trout your
fishery will have on any given day of the year. With such a formula
you could make plans for your business well into the future.  We will
talk about this in more detail in the next section.

<example xml:id="no-label">
<title>h</title>
<p>
  For example, suppose we have the following information about a
  certain function.  Can we sketch a reasonable graph of the function?
  \begin{multicols}{3}
    \begin{itemize}
    \item <m>y(1)=2 </m>
      \item <m>\dfdxat{y}{x}{1}=0</m>
                \item <m>\dfdxat{y}{x}{5}=0</m>
    \item <m>\eval{\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}}{x}{3}=0</m>
    \item <m>\eval{\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}}{x}{5}=0</m>
    \item <m>\dfdx{y}{x}\gt0</m>
      \leftline{for all <m>x\lt1</m>}
          \item <m> \dfdx{y}{x}\lt0</m>
      \leftline{for <m>1\lt x\lt 5</m> and <m>x\gt5</m>}
    \item <m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\gt0</m>
      \leftline{for <m>3\lt x\lt5</m>}
    \item <m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\lt0</m>
      \leftline{for <m>x\lt3</m>}
      \leftline{and <m>x\gt5</m>}
    \end{itemize}
  \end{multicols}
  
  Actually, this is easier than the previous problems, since intervals
  of increase, decrease, concave up, and concave down have already
  been determined for us.  For example, here are the tables for
  each.% 
        \begin{center}
    \begin{tabular}[h]{|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
                \hline 
                POTP \amp   \amp  <m>1</m>\amp  \amp  <m>5</m>\amp  \bigstrut 
      Interval \amp  <m>(-\infty,1)</m> \amp  \amp  <m>(1,5)</m> \amp \amp  <m>(5,\infty)</m>\bigstrut \hline\hline
      <m>\dfdx{y}{x}</m>\amp  <m>\dfdx{y}{x}\gt 0</m> \amp \amp  <m>\dfdx{y}{x}\lt 0</m> \amp \amp  <m>\dfdx{y}{x}\lt 0</m>\bigstrut 
      <m>y</m>\amp <m>\nearrow</m>\amp <m>2</m>\amp <m>\searrow</m>\amp <m>y(5)</m>\amp <m>\searrow</m>\bigstrut 
      \amp \amp \rotatebox{90}{{\tiny local max}}\amp \amp \rotatebox{90}{\textsf {\tiny neither}}\amp \bigstrut \hline
    \end{tabular}
  \end{center}
  
  \begin{center}
    \begin{tabular}[h]{|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
      \hline 
      PITP\amp   \amp  <m>3</m> \amp   \amp <m>5</m>\amp  \bigstrut 
      Interval \amp  <m>(-\infty,3)</m> \amp \amp  <m>(3,5)</m> \amp \amp  <m>(5,\infty)</m>\bigstrut \hline\hline
      <m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}</m>\amp  <m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\lt 0</m> \amp \amp  <m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\gt 0</m> \amp \amp 
      <m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\lt 0</m>\bigstrut 
      <m>y</m>\amp <m>\bigcap</m>\amp <m>y(3)</m>\amp <m>\bigcup</m>\amp <m>y(5)</m>\amp <m>\bigcap</m>\bigstrut 
      \amp \amp \rotatebox{90}{{\tiny inflection point}}\amp \amp \rotatebox{90}{{\tiny inflection point}}\amp \bigstrut \hline
    \end{tabular}
  \end{center}
  
  \begin{embeddedproblem}
    In this example we have <m>\eval{\dfdx{y}{x}}{x}{5}=0</m> and
    <m>\dfdx{y}{x}\lt 0</m> on the intervals <m>(1,5)</m> and
    <m>(5,\infty)</m>. Given that <m>\dfdxat{y}{x}{5}=0</m> and
    <m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\lt 0</m> when <m>x\gt 5</m>, did we really need to specify
    that <m>\dfdx{y}{x}\lt0</m> on the interval <m>(5,\infty)</m>?


                  \end{embeddedproblem}
  Based on the information given, the function <m>y=y(x)</m> has a local
  maximum at <m>x=1</m> and inflection points at <m>x=3</m> and <m>x=5.</m> A sketch
  of the graph might look something  like  this: 
  \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=3in,width=4in]{../Figures/Optimization6}}
</p>
</example>



<problem xml:id="no-label">
<introduction>
<p>
  Sketch the graph of <m>y=y(x)</m> which satisfies the given requirements.
</p>
</introduction>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 <m>y(-8)=10</m>,
           \leftline{<m> \dfdx{y}{x}\lt0</m> for all <m>x</m>}
           \leftline{ <m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\gt0</m>
             for all <m>x</m>.}
       </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 <m>y(0)=0</m>,
         <m>\dfdxat{y}{x}{0}=0</m>,
         <m>\geneval{\dfdx{y}{x}}{x\neq0}\gt0</m>,
         \leftline{<m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\lt0</m> for <m>x\lt0</m>,}
         \leftline{<m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\gt0</m> for <m>x\gt0</m>,}
     </p>
</statement>
</task>
</problem>
<!-- \begin{embeddedproblem}[(Continued on the next page)] -->
<!--   Sketch the graph of <m>y=y(x)</m> which satisfies the given requirements. -->
<!--          \begin{enumerate}[label={  (\alph*)}]  -->
<!--          \item <m>y(-8)=10</m>, -->
<!--            \leftline{<m> \dfdx{y}{x}\lt0</m> for all <m>x</m>} -->
<!--            \leftline{ <m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\gt0</m> -->
<!--              for all <m>x</m>.} -->
<!--        \item <m>y(0)=0</m>, -->
<!--          <m>\dfdxat{y}{x}{0}=0</m>, -->
<!--          <m>\geneval{\dfdx{y}{x}}{x\neq0}\gt0</m>, -->
<!--          \leftline{<m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\lt0</m> for <m>x\lt0</m>,} -->
<!--          \leftline{<m>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}\gt0</m> for <m>x\gt0</m>,} -->
