</section>
<section xml:id="no-label">
<title>Graphing with a Formula for \boldmath <m>\dfdx{y</title>

    Initial Value Problems}
\label{sec:graph-with-form-1}

  Problems}

<subsection xml:id="no-label">
<title>When \boldmath </m>\dfdx{y</title>


<example xml:id="no-label">
<title>h</title>
<p>
  Consider the IVP,
  <me>
  \dfdx{y}{t}=t(4-t),\ \         y(0)=0.
  </me>
  In Integral Calculus (probably your next math course) you will learn
  how to find <m>y(t)</m> explicitly. For now we will be satisfied with
  sketching an approximate graph of <m>y(t)</m>.

  Setting <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=0</m> and solving we see that <m>t=0</m> and <m>t=4</m> are
  the POTPs for <m>y(t)</m>.  Thus on each of the intervals <m>(-\infty,0)</m>,
  <m>(0,4)</m>, and <m>(4,\infty)</m> the graph of <m>y(t)</m> is either always
  increasing or always decreasing. We tabulate this information as follows:
  \begin{center}
    \begin{tabular}[h]{|c||c|c|c|c|c|}\hline
      POTP\amp \amp 0\amp  \amp 4\amp  \bigstrut  \hline
      Interval\amp <m>(-\infty,0)</m>\amp \amp  <m>(0,4)</m>\amp \amp  <m>(4,\infty)</m>\bigstrut  \hline\hline
      <m>y^\prime(t)</m>\amp  <m>\lt 0</m>\amp \amp  <m>\gt 0</m>\amp \amp  <m>\lt 0</m>\bigstrut  
      <m>y(t)</m> \amp  <m>\searrow </m>\amp 0\amp  <m>\nearrow </m> \amp <m>y(4)=</m>?\amp <m>\searrow </m>\bigstrut 
       \amp  \amp \rotatebox{90}{{\tiny {\tiny local min}}}\amp 
      \amp \rotatebox{90}{{\tiny {\tiny local max}}}\amp \bigstrut \hline
    \end{tabular}
  \end{center}
  Based on this table, we can see that <m>y(0)=0</m> is a local minimum and
  <m>y(4)</m> is a local maximum. Observe that we do not know the value of
  <m>y(4)</m>, only that it must be a local maximum. Nor do we have any way
  to determine the value of <m>y(4)</m> in this problem.
  
  We  proceed in a similar fashion to determine concavity. The second
  derivative is
  <me>
  \dfdxn{y}{t}{2}=\dfdx{(t(4-t))}{t}=4-2t.
  </me>
  Setting <m>\dfdxn{y}{t}{2}=0</m> and solving, we see that <m>t=2</m> is a PITP
  for <m>y(t)</m>.  Making a table as before we have
  \begin{center}
    \begin{tabular}[h]{|c||c|c|c|}\hline
      PITP\amp  \amp <m>2</m>\amp  \bigstrut \hline
      Interval \amp  <m>(-\infty,2)</m>\amp \amp  <m>(2,\infty)</m>\bigstrut \hline\hline
      <m>y^{\prime\prime}(t)</m>\amp  <m>\gt 0</m>\amp  \amp <m>\lt 0</m>\bigstrut 
      <m>y(t)</m>\amp  <m>\bigcup</m>\amp <m>0</m>\amp <m>\bigcap</m>\bigstrut 
      \amp \amp \rotatebox{90}{{\tiny inflection point}}\amp \bigstrut \hline
    \end{tabular}
  \end{center}
  Based on the table we see that the point <m>(2,y(2))</m> is an inflection point.
  
  We want to make a reasonable sketch of the graph of <m>y=y(t)</m> based
  on this information. But there is a lot of information in the tables
  and our graph needs to be consistent with all of it.  So we first
  organize all of our conclusions by plotting the transition points
  (both optimal and inflective) on the <m>t</m> axis and identifying the
  intervals where <m>y</m> is increasing, decreasing,
  concave up, or concave down.\vskip4mm 
  \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=1in,width=4in]{../Figures/IncDecChart1}}
  \vskip4mm 
  
   This information, along with the initial value,  <m>y(0)=0</m> allows us
   to provide a reasonable
  graph of <m>y(t).</m>
  \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=3in,width=5in]{../Figures/Optimization4}}
  
  From the initial condition in the IVP we know that <m>y(0)=0</m> but we
  have no information about the vertical coordinate of any other point
  on the graph. Thus, from the information given the scale Of
  this graph is unknowable. But we know that the graph above is
  reasonable because it is consistent with the data given in the
  IVP. This sort of graphical, qualitative analysis is the best we can
  do with the information we have but, as you see, we can glean a
  great deal of information about the ``shape'' of the graph of a
  function from its derivative alone.
</p>
</example>





\begin{embeddedproblem}   ;;; MULTILEVEL PROBLEM
  For each of the following  IVPs:
  \begin{enumerate}[label={  (\roman*)}]
  \item Find the intervals on which the graph of the solution is
    increasing and decreasing.  Identify the location all local
    extrema.
  \item Find the intervals on which the graph of the solution is
    concave upward and concave downward.  Identify the location of all
    inflection points.
  \item Plot a reasonable sketch of the graph for <m>y=y(t).</m>
    Approximate transition points using the appropriate technology or
    Newton's Method as necessary.
  \end{enumerate}
  \begin{enumerate}[label={  (\alph*)}]
    \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=t^2 (4-t),\ \  y(0)=0</m>.
    \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=t^2 (4+t),\ \  y(0)=0</m>.
    \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=\sin(t),\ \  y(0)=0</m>.
    \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=\sin(t),\ \  y(0)=2</m>.
    \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=\cos(t),\ \  y(0)=0</m>.
    \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=\sin(t)\cos(t),\ \  y(0)=\pi</m>.
    \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=t\sin(t),\ \  y(0)=0</m>.
    \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=5e^t-t,\ \  y(1)=1</m>.
    \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=-e^{-t}+\ln(t),\ \  y(1)=e</m>.
    \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=e^t\sin(2t),\ \  y(0)=1</m>.
    \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=\tan(t),\ \  y(0)=1</m>.
    \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=\sqrt{t},\ \         y(0)=1</m>
    \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=t^3-t,\ \      y(1)=3</m>
    \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=t-t^3,\ \       y(1)=3</m>   \hint{Compare this to
         problem (m).}
  \end{enumerate}
\end{embeddedproblem}


</subsection>
\subsection*{When \boldmath <m>\dfdx{y}{t}</m> depends on <m>y</m> alone.}
<blockquote>
<p>
To see a World in a Grain of Sand
And a Heaven in a Wild Flower 
Hold Infinity in the palm of your hand 
And Eternity in an
hour
</p>
<attribution>
<url href="https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/william-blake" visual="https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/william-blake">William
  Blake (0)</url>
</attribution>
</blockquote>


Consider the IVP
<me>
  \label{eq:ExpIVP2}
  \dfdx{y}{t}=y,\ y(0)=1.
</me>
This is the same IVP we approximated in
<xref ref="SECeulers-method">Section</xref>. The analysis we will do here is
related so you may find it useful to review that section before
proceeding.


As we've seen every IVP has two parts: a differential equation (in
this case, <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y</m>, and an
initial value (in this case, <m>y(0)=1</m> or equivalently, <m>(0,1)</m>).

<figure>
<caption>
This figure needs a caption.</caption>
<image source="images/DEGraph2.png" width="50%"/>
</figure>
<!-- \begin{wrapfigure}[]{r}{1in} -->
<!--   \captionsetup{labelformat=empty} -->
<!-- \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=1in,width=1in]{../Figures/DEGraph2}} -->
<!-- \label{fig:DEGraph2} -->
<!-- \end{wrapfigure} -->We will
focus on the differential equation first.
The differential equation <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y</m> says that at each point on
the graph of <m>y(t)</m> the slope of the graph is equal to the vertical
coordinate at that point. 
For example if <m>(0,1)</m> is a point on the graph of <m>y(t)</m>, then nearby  the
graph of <m>y(t)</m>  will look like  the orange part of the
sketch at the right.
On the other hand, if <m>(1,1)</m> is a point on the
graph of <m>y(t)</m> then near the point <m>(1,1)</m>, graph of <m>y(t)</m> will look like
the red graph in the sketch at the right. 

In fact, for any value of <m>t</m>, we know that if <m>(t,1)</m> is a point on
the graph of <m>y(t)</m> then the slope of the graph which passes through
that point will be parallel to the orange and red lines above (that
is, if a solution of the differential equation passes through a point
<m>(t,1)</m> then its slope will be equal to <m>1</m> at <m>(t,1)</m>).

<figure>
<caption>
This figure needs a caption.</caption>
<image source="images/DEGraph5.png" width="50%"/>
</figure>
<!-- \begin{wrapfigure}[]{l}{2.2in} -->
<!-- \captionsetup{labelformat=empty} -->
<!-- \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=.7in,width=2.2in]{../Figures/DEGraph5}} -->
<!-- \label{fig:DEGraph5} -->
<!-- \end{wrapfigure} -->
This is seen in the figure at the left where each black dot represents a
point with vertical coordinate equal to <m>1</m> and each orange segment
represents the graph of the curve that both satisfies the differential
equation from <xref ref="EQExpIVP2">IVP~\</xref>, and
passes through that point. % 
 
Similarly, if we know that <m>(t,2)</m> is a point on the graph of <m>y(t)</m>,
where <m>y(t)</m> both solves the differential equation from
<xref ref="EQExpIVP2">IVP~\</xref> and passes through that point, then the slope
at <m>(t,2)</m> will be <m>2</m>, as seen in the following sketch. 
 
<image source="images/DEGraph7.png" width="60%" />
<!-- \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=.7in,width=2in]{../Figures/DEGraph7}} -->



By tagging more  points in the plane in the same way we get the image below.

<image source="images/DEGraph9.png" width="60%" />
<!-- \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=2in,width=3.5in]{../Figures/DEGraph9}} -->
A sketch like this is called a <term>slope field</term>. The short line
segment at each point, <m>(a,b)</m>, is a short section of the graph of the
function\aside{Actually the Principle of Local Linearity applies so it
  is a short section of the line tangent at <m>(a,b)</m>.} which
satisfies the differential equation <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y</m>. If we know where
to start (i.e., if we have an initial condition) the slope field
allows us to determine the shape of the entire graph.

For example to  sketch the graph of <m>y(t)</m> if it passes through the
point <m>(2,3)</m>,
we simply follow the line segments in our slope field starting at that
point. This is the black graph in the sketch below. The graph of the
<m>y(t)</m> that passes through the point <m>(5,5)</m> is shown in red below,
and the graph that passes through the point <m>(-1,-1.25)</m> is shown in
blue.

<image source="images/DEGraph8.png" width="60%" />
<!-- \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=3.3in,width=3.7in]{../Figures/DEGraph8}} -->



<exercise xml:id="no-label">
<statement>
<p>
<xref ref="EQExpIVP2">IVP~\</xref> has the initial condition, <m>y(0)=1.</m> Plot the
point <m>(0,1)</m> and use this slope field to sketch the solution of
<xref ref="EQExpIVP2">IVP~\</xref>. Compare your solution with the  approximation
we obtained in <xref ref="SECeulers-method">Section~</xref>). Do they look like
the same solution?
</p>
</statement>
</exercise>

<problem xml:id="no-label">
<introduction>
<p>
</p>
</introduction>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 Confirm that <m>y(t)=3e^{t-2}</m> is the solution of the 
    IVP <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y</m>, <m>y(2)=3</m>. (This is the black graph above.)
  </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 Confirm that <m>y(t)=5e^{t-5}</m> is the solution of the 
    IVP <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y</m>, <m>y(5)=5</m>. (This is the red graph above.)
  </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 Based on parts (a) and (b) guess what the solution of the IVP
    <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y</m>, <m>y(-1)=-2</m> will be. Confirm that your guess is
    correct. {If you guess wrong, guess again.}
    </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 Based on parts (a) and (b), and (c) make a conjecture what the solution of the IVP
    <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y</m>, <m>y(a)=b</m> will be. Confirm that your guess is
    correct. 
  </p>
</statement>
</task>
</problem>
<!-- \begin{embeddedproblem-enumerate}[Find the Pattern] -->
<!--   \begin{enumerate}[label={  (\alph*)}]  -->
<!--   \item Confirm that <m>y(t)=3e^{t-2}</m> is the solution of the  -->
<!--     IVP <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y</m>, <m>y(2)=3</m>. (This is the black graph above.) -->
<!--   \item Confirm that <m>y(t)=5e^{t-5}</m> is the solution of the  -->
<!--     IVP <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y</m>, <m>y(5)=5</m>. (This is the red graph above.) -->
<!--   \item Based on parts (a) and (b) guess what the solution of the IVP -->
<!--     <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y</m>, <m>y(-1)=-2</m> will be. Confirm that your guess is -->
<!--     correct. {If you guess wrong, guess again.} -->
<!--     \item Based on parts (a) and (b), and (c) make a conjecture what the solution of the IVP -->
<!--     <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y</m>, <m>y(a)=b</m> will be. Confirm that your guess is -->
<!--     correct.  -->
<!--   \end{enumerate} -->
<!-- \end{embeddedproblem-enumerate} -->


To sketch the graph of the solution of a given  IVP  begin by
drawing  the <term>slope field</term> for the differential equation. Then 
plot the  value and follow the slope field to sketch the graph.

<problem xml:id="no-label">
<introduction>
<p>
  For each of the following IVPs sketch the \term{slope field} in the
  ranges given and use your slope field to sketch the solution of the
  IVP. 
  \comment{It is easiest to begin by sketching slopes at integer
    coordinate points but that doesn't always give you a clear
    picture. Begin with the integer coordinate points and then fill in
    between them to get a clearer sense of the graphs.}
</p>
</introduction>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=\sqrt{y}</m>,
      \leftline{<m>y(0)=1</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>-5\le t</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>y\ge0</m>}
    </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y^2</m>,
      \leftline{ <m>y(-1)=-2</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>-5\le t\le 5</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>-5\le y\le 5</m>}
    </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=(y-1)^2</m>,
      \leftline{<m>y(1)=0</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>-5\le t\le 5</m>,} 
      \leftline{<m>-5\le y\le 5</m>}
    </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y(y-2)</m>,
      \leftline{<m>y(1)=1</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>-1\le x\le 1</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>-2\le y\le 3</m>}
    </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y(2-y)</m>,
      \leftline{<m>y(1)=1</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>-1\le t\le 1</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>-2\le y\le 3</m>}
    </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=(y^2-1)</m>,
      \leftline{<m>y(0)=1</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>-2\le t\le 2</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>-2\le y\le 2</m>}
  </p>
</statement>
</task>
</problem>
<!-- \begin{embeddedproblem} -->
<!--   For each of the following IVPs sketch the \term{slope field} in the -->
<!--   ranges given and use your slope field to sketch the solution of the -->
<!--   IVP.  -->
<!--   \comment{It is easiest to begin by sketching slopes at integer -->
<!--     coordinate points but that doesn't always give you a clear -->
<!--     picture. Begin with the integer coordinate points and then fill in -->
<!--     between them to get a clearer sense of the graphs.} -->
<!--   \begin{enumerate}[label={  (\alph*)}]  -->
<!--     \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=\sqrt{y}</m>, -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>y(0)=1</m>,} -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>-5\le t</m>,} -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>y\ge0</m>} -->
<!--     \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y^2</m>, -->
<!--       \leftline{ <m>y(-1)=-2</m>,} -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>-5\le t\le 5</m>,} -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>-5\le y\le 5</m>} -->
<!--     \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=(y-1)^2</m>, -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>y(1)=0</m>,} -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>-5\le t\le 5</m>,}  -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>-5\le y\le 5</m>} -->
<!--     \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y(y-2)</m>, -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>y(1)=1</m>,} -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>-1\le x\le 1</m>,} -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>-2\le y\le 3</m>} -->
<!--     \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=y(2-y)</m>, -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>y(1)=1</m>,} -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>-1\le t\le 1</m>,} -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>-2\le y\le 3</m>} -->
<!--     \item <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=(y^2-1)</m>, -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>y(0)=1</m>,} -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>-2\le t\le 2</m>,} -->
<!--       \leftline{<m>-2\le y\le 2</m>} -->
<!--   \end{enumerate} -->
<!-- \end{embeddedproblem} -->

So far we've examined the situation when <m>\dfdx{y}{t}</m> depends on <m>t</m>
alone: <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=f(t)</m> and when <m>\dfdx{y}{t}</m> depends on <m>y</m> alone:
<m>\dfdx{y}{t}=f(y)</m>. But, of course, it could happen at <m>\dfdx{y}{t}</m>
depends on both <m>y</m> and <m>t</m>:<m>\dfdx{y}{t}=f(t,y)</m>. Analytically, this
is a more complex situation. However it is possible, and quite useful,
to get a qualitative sketch of the solution of an IVP from the slope
field.

<problem xml:id="no-label">
<introduction>
<p>
  For each of the following IVPs draw The \term{slope field} in the
  ranges given and use your slope field to sketch the solution of the
  IVP.
</p>
</introduction>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=yt</m>,
      \leftline{<m>y(0)=1</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>-3\le t\le 3</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>y\ge0</m>}
    </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=\frac{y}{t^2+1}</m>,
      \leftline{<m>y(1)=0</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>-5\le x\le 5</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>-5\le y\le 5</m>}
    </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=ye^x</m>,
      \leftline{<m>y(-4)=2</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>-5\le t\le 5</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>-5\le y\le 5</m>}
    </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=ye^{-x}</m>,
      \leftline{<m>y(0)=2</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>0\le t\le 5</m>,}
      \leftline{<m>-5\le y\le 5</m>}
  </p>
</statement>
</task>
</problem>
